e4LBlbOGhwE.title: Jazz at Lincoln Center Presents: Let Freedom Swing — From Spirituals to Swing
e4LBlbOGhwE.description:
ADDITIONAL RESOURCES: http://www.jazz.org/let-freedom-swing/

ABOUT THE SHOW:
Artists from Jazz at Lincoln Center’s Let Freedom Swing are joined by legendary North Carolina Gospel duo the Branchettes and special guest bassist and vocalist Bill Crow for a concert devoted to music that gives us strength and support.

PERFORMERS:
Lena Mae Perry – vocals
Angela Kent – vocals, piano
Brianna Thomas – vocals
Bruce Harris – trumpet
Alphonso Horne – trumpet, vocals
Gabrielle Murphy – alto saxophone
Corbin Jones – bass, baritone vocals
Bill Crow – bass, vocals
Norman Edwards – drums
Justin Poindexter – guitar
Jake Blasini – emcee

ABOUTLET FREEDOM SWING
Let Freedom Swing brings outstanding jazz artists and performances to school and community audiences. Inspired by conversations between former U.S. Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor and jazz musician Wynton Marsalis, Let Freedom Swing has performed thousands of concerts in the U.S. and internationally since launching in 2013, reaching over half a million students with live jazz concerts.

TZZr5-VANqA.title: Jazz at Lincoln Center Presents: Let Freedom Swing
TZZr5-VANqA.description:
ADDITIONAL RESOURCES: http://www.jazz.org/let-freedom-swing/

ABOUT THE SHOW
It’s impossible to separate the history of jazz from the struggle for civil and human rights. Tonight’s performance is all about honoring that legacy as jazz musicians join forces to pay tribute to the genre’s uniquely American heritage. In this special pre-election day concert, Jazz at Lincoln Center will showcase the uniquely democratic principles of our music. With emphasis on the blues, a top flight ensemble of up-and-coming jazz artists will illustrate the diverse origins and collective spirit that have made jazz America’s most significant artistic contribution.

PERFORMERS
Shenel Johns, vocals 
Jonathan Thomas, piano 
Endea Owens, bass 
Norman Edwards, drums 
Alphonso Horne, trumpet 
Godwin Louis, alto saxophone 
Justin Poindexter, guitar 
Jake Blasini, emcee

ABOUT LET FREEDOM SWING
Let Freedom Swing brings outstanding jazz artists and performances to school and community audiences. Inspired by conversations between former U.S. Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor and jazz musician Wynton Marsalis, Let Freedom Swing includes three jazz concerts: Jazz and Democracy, Jazz and the Great Migration, and Jazz and Civil Rights. Presented in 11 cities around the world, Let Freedom Swing reaches over 85,000 students in over 550 concerts annually.

This Live from Dizzy's performance was filmed at Frederick P. Rose Hall in New York City in accordance with the New York State Department of Health Interim Guidance on Media Production during the Covid-19 Emergency.

0KzYYKPMiBg.title: Essentially Ellington 2021: Virtual Jam Session
0KzYYKPMiBg.description:
For the 26th annual Essentially Ellington, we invited musicians to sit in on a virtual Jam Session. Select students from each finalist band perform alongside the Jazz at Lincoln Center Orchestra, whose members recorded from home. Check out some of the finest high school musicians in the world with these world-class swingers!

Learn more about Essentially Ellington: https://academy.jazz.org/ee/

To learn more about Jazz at Lincoln Center, visit us at http://www.jazz.org

Rif69A89yyY.title: We Recite the Blues You Write: Jazz at Lincoln Center Plays Student Blues Songs
Rif69A89yyY.description:
In April 2020, we invited students to write an original blues about whatever they might be feeling. We received thousands of lyric submissions from around the world. Here are some of our favorites, interpreted in the best way we know how.



To learn more about Jazz at Lincoln Center, visit us at http://www.jazz.org
